00:02:39.360 --> 00:02:41.280
CAROL DWECK: I was
always interested

00:02:41.280 --> 00:02:48.300
in why some people wilted
in the face of failure,

00:02:48.300 --> 00:02:51.230
shied away from
challenges, when people

00:02:51.230 --> 00:02:55.910
who are no more talented or
able were embracing challenges

00:02:55.910 --> 00:02:58.930
and thriving in the
face of failure.

00:02:58.930 --> 00:03:03.650
Ultimately this led to our
discovery of the mindsets.

00:03:03.650 --> 00:03:07.400
And what we found was that some
people believe their talents

00:03:07.400 --> 00:03:10.150
and abilities are just these
fixed traits-- you have

00:03:10.150 --> 00:03:12.960
a certain amount and that's it.

00:03:12.960 --> 00:03:16.090
But other people believe
talents and abilities

00:03:16.090 --> 00:03:19.450
can be developed through
hard work, good strategies,

00:03:19.450 --> 00:03:22.980
good mentoring from others.

00:03:22.980 --> 00:03:29.860
Through years of work, we found
that having a fixed mindset led

00:03:29.860 --> 00:03:33.320
you to be afraid of
challenges that might unmask

00:03:33.320 --> 00:03:37.230
your deficiencies,
made you withdraw

00:03:37.230 --> 00:03:40.029
in the face of difficulty
because you felt stupid.

00:03:40.029 --> 00:03:41.320
You didn't want to feel stupid.

00:03:41.320 --> 00:03:43.840
You didn't want other people
to think you're stupid.

00:03:43.840 --> 00:03:45.990
Whereas having this
growth mindset,

00:03:45.990 --> 00:03:50.780
the idea that your abilities
could be developed,

00:03:50.780 --> 00:03:52.480
made you think,
why waste my time

00:03:52.480 --> 00:03:55.290
looking smart when I
could be getting smarter?

00:03:55.290 --> 00:03:58.350
And I do that through
taking on challenges.

00:03:58.350 --> 00:04:02.060
I do that through
seeing them through.

